description: Dogs surround a dead bear. Using dogs for bear hunting is illegal in Washington.
A screenshot from a video of Haynes and S. Dills killing a bear as it crosses a road to get away from dogs.
W. Haynes posing with a bear. These photos were sent to Haynes from a friend's phone, later used to locate the hunt by WDFW officials.
One of the hunters looks at a treed bear during a hunt on September 19, 2015.
A photo of hunting dogs taken by W. Haynes. The dogs wear GPS tracking collars.
W. Haynes posing with his shotgun, which was later recovered from his home. According to WDFW interviews with Haynes, the blood splatter is from a bear killed that day.
Hunters and dogs at the base of a tree, looking up at a bear.
Hounds surround a dead bear. No GPS coordinates were recovered from thsi photo, but cellular tower pings data was used by WDFW detectives to determine the hunt's location.
A redacted photo from the WDFW case file of a hunter with a bobcat, taken from Haynes' phone.
Investigator photo of bones from the site of a bear hunt.
Investigator photo of bones from the site of an illegal elk hunt.
Photo from Haynes' phone of a treed bobcat, taken down the site of a hunting rifle.
J. Dills standing over a dead elk, in a photo recovered from Haynes' phone. Investigators later traced this photo to the same location using GPS metadata.
Investigator photo of a skull at the site of a bear hunt.
Investigator photo of a jawbone at the site of a bear hunt.
WDFW GPS device at the location
Photo of Haynes with a dead bear.
Shotgun slug recovered from the bear remains
Dogs surrounding a dead bear.
Investigators lay out bones found at the site of a bear hunt.
Haynes posing with an elk near the Spirit Lake Highway.
